# Environment Variables Setup

This document lists all the required environment variables for the E-Nutrition Backend application.

## Required Environment Variables

### General Configuration
```env
NODE_ENV=develop
PORT=3000
```

### Database Configuration
```env
DB_HOST=localhost
DB_PORT=5432
DB_USERNAME=postgres
DB_PASSWORD=your-database-password
DB_NAME=e_nutrition_db
DB_TYPE=postgres
MAX_POOL_SIZE=10
MIN_POOL_SIZE=2
`````

### JWT Configuration
```env
JWT_SECRET=your-super-secret-jwt-key-here-change-in-production
JWT_EXPIRES_IN=24h
SALT_ROUNDS=10
```

### S3 Bucket Configuration (Wasabi/S3 Compatible)
```env
BUCKET_NAME=your-bucket-name
BUCKET_REGION=us-east-1
BUCKET_ACCESS_KEY_ID=your-access-key-id
BUCKET_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=your-secret-access-key
BUCKET_ENDPOINT=https://s3.wasabisys.com
INTERNAL_BUCKET_NAME=your-internal-bucket-name
```

### User Configuration
```env
DEFAULT_USER_NAME=Admin
DEFAULT_PASSWORD=TempPass123!
```

### File Size Limits
```env
IMAGE_FILE_SIZE=5MB
VIDEO_FILE_SIZE=100MB
AUDIO_FILE_SIZE=50MB
IMAGE_FIELD_SIZE=10MB
```

### SendGrid Email Configuration
```env
SEND_GRID_API_KEY=your-sendgrid-api-key-here
```

### Support Email Configuration
```env
SUPPORT_SENDER_EMAIL=noreply@yourdomain.com
```

### Additional Environment Variables (for backward compatibility)
```env
JWT_ENCRYPTION_KEY=your-super-secret-jwt-key-here-change-in-production
JWT_TOKEN_EXPIRY_TIME=86400
SALT_ROUND=10
BUCKET_NAME=your-bucket-name
WASABI_ACCESSS_KEY_ID=your-access-key-id
WASABI_SECRET_KEY=your-secret-access-key
SUPPORT_EMAIL=support@yourdomain.com
SECURITY_EMAIL=security@yourdomain.com
```

## Setup Instructions

1. Copy the environment variables above to your `.env` file
2. Replace all placeholder values with your actual configuration
3. Ensure your database is running and accessible
4. Configure your S3/Wasabi bucket credentials
5. Set up SendGrid for email functionality
6. Configure Google OAuth if needed
7. Set up Elasticsearch if you plan to use search functionality

## Security Notes

- **Never commit your `.env` file to version control**
- Use strong, unique secrets for JWT and encryption keys
- Change default passwords in production
- Use environment-specific configurations for different deployments
- Regularly rotate your API keys and secrets

## Validation

The application uses Zod schema validation to ensure all required environment variables are present and properly formatted. If any required variables are missing, the application will fail to start with a clear error message.
